Hmm, I'm not sure this equivalence is interesting given that it is the combination of `Sym.oneEquiv` and `alpha ~= {a : alpha // True}`
How do you combine them? I'm having trouble with it, I can't identify `ofSym a` with `indiscrete 1`.
I guess my problem is that I don't know how to prove `msymm_one` from https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/12572 without this lemma.
I'll have a look tomorrow evening. Please remind me if I forget
I made a commit on the other branch removing the lemma. I don't quite like the proof, but it works. I can either revert that commit or remove the lemma here, let me know which one is preferred.
I am very sure I can golf your proof in the other PR, so I would prefer if you removed the equivalence from here

```suggestion
@[simp] lemma ofSym_map (e : σ ≃ τ) (s : Sym σ n) :
```

```suggestion
@[simp] lemma ofSym_one (s : Sym σ 1) : ofSym s = indiscrete 1 := by
```

This is devoid of information. I already know this from the *type* of the declaration. However I would like to know what's going on inside the *body*. Can you change it to something like 
```suggestion
/-- `a ↦ {a}` as an equivalence between `α` and `Sym α 1`. -/
```
